1. Linear Data Structures

A linear data structure is a type of data structure in which elements are arranged sequentially in a single line. Each element (except the first and last) has one predecessor and one successor.

Characteristics:
Elements are stored in a linear order.
Traversal happens sequentially (one by one).
Easier to implement compared to non-linear structures.

Examples:
Arrays
Linked Lists
Stacks
Queues

a. Arrays

An array is a data structure that stores a collection of elements of the same type in contiguous memory locations. Each element is accessed using an index (position).

Key points:
Fixed size (in most languages).
Fast access using index (e.g., arr[2]).
Elements stored next to each other in memory.

b. Linked Lists

A linked list is a linear data structure where elements (called nodes) are not stored in contiguous memory. Each node contains:

Data
A reference (pointer) to the next node in the list.
Key points:
Dynamic size.
Efficient insertion and deletion.
Sequential access (cannot directly access by index).

c. Stacks

A stack is a linear data structure that follows the LIFO principle (Last In, First Out).

Key operations:

Push: Add an element to the top.
Pop: Remove the top element.
Peek/Top: View the top element.

d. Queues

A queue is a linear data structure that follows the FIFO principle (First In, First Out).

Key operations:

Enqueue: Add element at the rear.
Dequeue: Remove element from the front.

