2. Non-Linear Data Structures

A non-linear data structure is a structure where elements are not arranged sequentially. Instead, elements are connected in a hierarchical or network-like structure.

Characteristics:

One element can connect to multiple elements.
Data is stored in different levels or branches.
Traversal follows multiple paths.

Examples:

Trees
Graphs


a. Trees

A tree is a non-linear data structure that organizes data in a hierarchical structure. It consists of nodes connected by edges, with one top node called the root.

Key characteristics:

The top element is called the root.
Each node may have child nodes.
Nodes are connected in parent–child relationships.
There are no cycles.

b. Graphs

A graph is a non-linear data structure consisting of a set of vertices (nodes) connected by edges. Graphs are used to represent relationships between objects.

Key characteristics:

Nodes are called vertices.
Connections are called edges.
Can be directed or undirected.
Can contain cycles.

c. Heaps

A heap is a special type of binary tree that satisfies the heap property. It is commonly used to implement priority queues.

Types of heaps:

1. Max Heap

The parent node is greater than or equal to its children.
The largest element is at the root.

2. Min Heap

The parent node is smaller than or equal to its children.
The smallest element is at the root.

================ 5 Algorithm Patterns + Big-O =================

1) Frequency Counter
   -----------------
   Count occurrences instead of nested loops.
   Example: Check if two arrays have the same elements.
   [a, b, a, c]  →  {a:2, b:1, c:1}
   Big-O: O(n)  ✅ linear growth

2) Multiple Pointers
   -----------------
   Use two pointers on sorted arrays to avoid nested loops.
   Example: Find pair with sum.
   Left → 1       Right → 7
   Move inward depending on sum.
   Big-O: O(n)  ✅ linear

3) Sliding Window
   -----------------
   Maintain a “window” and move it along array/string.
   Example: Max sum of 3 consecutive numbers.
   [2,1,5,1,3,2] → windows: [2,1,5], [1,5,1], [5,1,3], [1,3,2]
   Big-O: O(n) ✅ linear

4) Divide & Conquer
   -----------------
   Split problem, solve smaller pieces, combine.
   Example: Binary search in sorted array.
   [2,4,6,8,10,12,14] → cut in half repeatedly
   Big-O: O(log n) ✅ logarithmic growth

5) Recursion / Backtracking
   -----------------
   Solve problem by solving smaller versions of itself.
   Example: Factorial or tree traversal.
       3 * Factorial(2)
            2 * Factorial(1)
                 1 → base case
   Big-O: O(n) for simple recursion, O(2^n) for branching (like subsets/permutations)

==================================================================
Quick visual summary
Pattern	Big-O	Notes
Frequency Counter	O(n)	Count items efficiently
Multiple Pointers	O(n)	Avoid nested loops
Sliding Window	O(n)	Good for subarrays/substrings
Divide & Conquer	O(log n)–O(n log n)	Cuts problem in half, like binary search
Recursion / Backtracking	O(n)–O(2ⁿ)	Depends on branching depth

💡 Takeaway:

O(n²) only happens with nested work or multiple branches in recursion.

Most interview problems are solved with one of these 5 patterns efficiently.

If you visualize the pattern + Big-O, you instantly know which approach will scale.

================ Algorithm Pattern Flowchart =================

Start → What’s the problem?

1) Need to compare/count items? → Frequency Counter (O(n))
   Example: Are two arrays made of the same elements?

2) Working with a sorted array or string? → Multiple Pointers (O(n))
   Example: Find pair with target sum, remove duplicates

3) Need to find max/min in a contiguous subarray or substring? → Sliding Window (O(n))
   Example: Max sum of 3 consecutive numbers, longest substring without repeating characters

4) Can you divide problem into smaller pieces? → Divide & Conquer (O(log n) / O(n log n))
   Example: Binary search, merge sort, large dataset searches

5) Problem involves exploring all possibilities or branching paths? → Recursion / Backtracking (O(n) – O(2ⁿ))
   Example: Factorial, subsets, permutations, tree traversal, maze/pathfinding

6) None of the above → Consider brute-force (O(n²) or worse) or rethink data structure
   Example: Nested loops that can be optimized

